{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_roseheath_ver01/data/sn92070146/00414188849/1937112401/0066.xml":{"full_text":"|B KINGING\nALL THF MWI\nTO IMPEHIAI\n\u25bcalley\nThe Best Rule of Ail\nFor Highway Safety\nTen persons were injured on Imperial\ncounty highways last weekend, just as\nthe imperial County Safety council was\nperfecting plans for traffic schools for\nerring motorists. The list of accidents\nproves beyond the shadow of a doubt\nthe need for some such program as that\nplanned by the safety council, but it\nproves also the need for a quality which\n100 few motorists seem to possess\u2014com\nmon sense.\nA traffic school can teach the rules\nof the road and the rules of courtesy.\nWhether it can drill common sense into\nheads where that item seems to be absent\nis another matter.\nSince automobiles were young there\nhas been one unfailing rule by which\nmore motorists have kept out of acci\ndents than by any other. If the traffic\nschools can implant this rule in the\nminds uf all drivers who attend it, our\nhighways will be far safer places for\ntravel. The rule, applicable to every\ndriver, is this:\nAlways drive as though the persons\nbehind the wheels of every other auto\nmobile are insane. Drive as though every\nother driver were intending to crash\ninto you if he can. Drive safely yourself,\nremembering that the other fellow will\nnot.\nSmall Homes and\nCity Beautification\nSmall home owners and renters in El\nCentro have an opportunity as good or\nbetter than the owners of large homes\nto profit from the City Beautification\ncontest now being carried on by civic\ngroups here, inc\u2019uding the El Centro\nchamber of commerce and the city of\nEl Centro. Not only is their chance to\nshare in prizes good, but their personal\nprofit from more attractive homes\nshould be greater.\nAll this is true because it is the small\nhomes in El Centro which are most sadly\nin need of beautification, and this beau\ntification contest does not specify that\nthe most beautiful garden or yard shall\nwin first place. The first prize will go\nto the place which shows most improve\nment.\nA small home can be just as attrac\ntive as a larger, more expensive one. It\nis the effort and planning put into it\nthat makes a place attractive. A $25,000\nhome can be just as unattractive as a\nS2OOO one, but it is seldom that the own\ners or leasees of the finer homes allow\ntheir yards and homes to deteriorate.\nUnfortunately, those living in smaller\nplaces often do.\nA city of smal homes is more attrac\ntive than a city of large ones, when the\nsmall homes are carefully groomed and\nthe yards and gardens are kept in good\nshape.\nIt is up to the small home owners\nand renters to make El Centro\u2019s city\nbeautification campaign a success.\nManufacturing the Future\nOn the All-American Canal\nIn a current series of photographs, the\nImperial Valley Press and The Morn\ning Post are attempting to show resi\ndents of Imperial Valley the progress\nof work on the All American canal. The\nseries is interesting, the photographs\nshow fascinating phases of the construc\ntion job, and the pictures show that\nwork is farther along than most of us\nrealize\u2014but there never was any series\nof photographs which could do justice\nto this gigantic industry that is even\nnow manufacuring the future for Impe\nrial Valley.\nYou should study these photographs,\nperhaps, but they should be only \u201csup\nplemental reading.\u201d First you should\nvisit the All American canal to. see in\ni -rson the work that is going on.\nOut Our Way Williams\n/T GOIM\u2019 south 'V WELL, you KNOW 1/OH WELL y Pt\npcR. TM\u2018 WINTER I HAVEN\u2019T ANS' V NO IWN HE LIKES\nL BREEZY? CAR, RADIO, I WONPER IT, THEM HE'S\n00514 MOW PO i CANARY, POLICE I HE CAN GOT EVERYTHING/\nSOU DO IT? WHY I DOG, TUXEDO, TAKE A BIRP\n\u2022I HAETA &LM/ A POLO PONIES, LONG HAVE MUCH BUT\nPOSTAGE STAMP/ KIDS ER WIFE, RESTS/ WORMS, AN\nER NOTHIN' /HE AIN'T STILUTHEY\n.s' like that. got sing more\np NOTHIN' J\\ than we\n\u25a0I 1 f 1771\nA zZT- TV r A A\n-\"m nil ff lah\n\u25a0L V\ni <or* <-l\u00bb sond 1 \u2014FREE POM.\nX. Vt> u\u00abnt wt\nThoughts for the Day\nBehold, happy is the man whom God correcteth:\ntherefore despise not thou the chastening of the\nAlmighty.\u2014Job 55:17.\nNews Behind the News\nWire Tapping Squabble\nWASHINGTON \u2014Secretary \u201cHonest Harold\"\nIckes has just undertaken to assure top officials\nof PWA and the Interior Department that they\nare not being subjected to wire tapping, dicta\nphone planting and other espionage.\nIckes acted to solve a cocxeyed situation\nResponsible, highly-paid officials were com\nplaining to each other of tapped telephone con\nversations, of surveillance of visitors to their\noffices and of being shadowed outside\nSome officials even had private electricians\nsearch their offices for possible dictaphones or\nhidden wires. Ickes himself apparently to make\nsure no one was snooping without his knowl\nedge, had the telephone company check impor\ntant offices recently\u2014including his own.\nSo the secretary summoned several dozen\nofficials to a departmental conference He said\nhe had heard some were disturbed by talk of\nwire-tapping and dictaphones, that there had\nbeen some of that once, but wasn\u2019t any more\nHe hadn\u2019t delegated the authority for such\nmeasures to anyone; he had retained it.\nThen up spoke Nathan Straus, the new ad\nministrator of the U. S. Housing Authority. Bear\nin mind that Straus, whose agency operates\nautonomously under the Interior Department,\nwas bitterly opposed for his job by Ickes.\nStraus demanded to know- whether Ickes had\nany rtght to tap wires and so on He added\nhis opinion that it was a criminal offense.\nIckes snapped back that he was able to run\nhis own department.\n\u201cI'm going to get an opinion from the attor\nney general about it.\" insisted Straus, whose\nown telephones connect through the Interior\nswitchboard.\n\u201cThe attorney general only gives opinions to\nheads of departments,\u201d said Ickes.\n\u201cWell, you're the head of a department.\"\nreturned Straus, indicating that he would still\nseek an opinion if Ickes didn\u2019t.\nThe meeting broke up amid considerable\nembarrassment and numerous predictions ot\nfurther hostilities.\nOfficial speeches most worth watching, next\nto the President\u2019s are those of Jimmy Roosevelt,\nhis son and secretary.\nJimmy has been and occasionally will be\nused to release occasional trial balloons. He\nspoke with entire confidence, if not with some\nsignificance, when he recently told a Catholic\nyouth organization at Chicago:\n\"American democracy is prepared today to\ndo whatever needs to be done and to go as\nfar as it needs to go to keep the fate of many\nfrom falling back into control of the few.\"\nSenator Harry Byrd of Virginia criticized a\nrural resettlement housing project in his state\nso violently that some drastic economies were\nmade. Scheduled plumbing installations were\nabandoned in favor of small houses to the rear.\nThe tenants now call these structures \"Byrd\nhouses.\u201d\nOther Editors Say\nFREEDOM OF THE HIGHWAYS\n(South Coast News)\nWhen the teamsters union in Los Angeles\ntold the Associated Farmers of California. \u201cYou\ncannot use the public highways unless you\nunionize truck drivers,\u201d Col. Walter E. Garrison.\nLodi farmer, who won his title in France, replied,\n\u201cThe freedom of the highways is just as sacred\nto the farmers as freedom of speech.\u201d\nThe farmers won the right to haul their own\nproducts in their ow.i trucks with their own\ndrivers.\nThe bald statement from the union leaders\nthat the farmers could not use their own drivers\nwas a challenge that struck at the very heart\nof California's greatest industry, agriculture. The\nunions stepped on the wrong toes when they\nundertook to tell the farmer what he can do\nand cannot do.\nLong the target of slickers, grafters and\nunion racketeers, the farmer has taken all he\nintends to take. The teamsters wanted to get\nthe six hundred million dollar industry in their\npower so they could squeeze the earnings of the\nfarmer into their own pockets.\nNot only is freedom of the highways sacred,\nbut the freedom of life and liberty is more\nsacred, and the general public is getting \u201cfed\nup\" on the \u201cmusts\" shoved down their throats\nby the men who call themselves leaders of\nlabor.\nIt has taken a long time for the tide to begin\nto turn against the tyranny of American racket\neering. but the trip down the long lane has\nbeen made, and the turn has been reached.\nThere has been no freedom along the high\nway to happinss for the great middle class of\nAmerica since two men decided to become the\ncountry\u2019s Simon Legrees. But they have violated\nthe sacredness of that freedom. The great\nmiddle class and the farmers have had enough.\nIt\u2019s their turn pretty soon, and they will do a\nnice sweet job when they get just a bit more\nriled.\nEditorials and Comment\nYour Husband Has Met with An Accident\n\nI :Fi 7A E\nft L H\na L-\n.1\u00ae\nHew York Day by Day\nNEW YORK, Nov. 24.\u2014N0 one\nhas more successfully combined\npoetry with business than Margaret\nFishback. As a highly paid copy\nwriter and execu-1\ntive in a large de\npartment store,\nshe also finds time\nto turn out salable\nbooks of poetry'\nfrom time to timed\nYoung, bright\neyed, and with\nhair the color of\npulled taffy, she\nlong poetized her!\nspinsterhood. And\nthen one day in\nher store she met'\na rug buyer\u2014of all people\u2014fell in\nlove and married. Her next book\nof verse had the apologetic title:\n\"I Take it Back.\u201d\nShe was also a confirmed cliff\ndweller, to whom the city was the\nonly livable place. But that was\nbefore her marriage. Her husband\ntook her to a home in the suburbs\nand now she spends her spare time\nworking in the garden and sighing\nover leaving it daily for the city.\nHowever. Miss Fishback is not the\nonly successful poet to win fame\nat a desk in an advertising office.\nOgden Nash was dashing off copy\nfor a book publishing concern when\nbetween tasks he discovered his\njingles were salable. And quit ev\nerything to woo the muse.\nThere are minnesingers to whom\nverse comes as natural as breath\ning. Gelett Burgess can walk along\nthe street and sing-song poems of\nbeauty and comedy from the things\nhe sees en passant. The columnist\nF. P. A. Is said to have the most\nremarkable memory for poetry of\nall modern bards. Given the first\nline of any verse from the Oxford\ncollection or the various anthologies,\nhe can complete it. Meredith\nNicholson, while better known as\nan essayist and novelist, is so poeti\ncally minded that any beautiful\nscene will inspire him to murmur\nhis thoughts in rhyme. But only to\nclose friends. Frank Sullivan likes\nto scurry up Parnassus when no\nbody is looking, too.\nPoetry appreciation begins\u2014like\nso many good things\u2014for most peo\nple at 40. Before that time much\nof the poetry, save for a few saltier\nclassics of the barrooms when one\nis a bit maudlin, bored me no end.\nThe Grab Bag\nOne-Minute Test\n1. Who is U. S. ambassador to\nChina?\n2. When does winter begin (of\nficially) this year?\n3. What two newspaper publish\ners contested for the U. S. presi\ndency in 1920?\nHints on Etiquette\nAn envelope should always bear\nthe full name of the person to\nwhom the letter is sent.\nWords of Wisdom\nPoverty possesses this disease,\nthat through want it teaches man\nto do evil \u2014Euripides.\nToday\u2019s Horoscope\nMany persons whose birthday oc\ncurs today constantly seek recog\nnition. The desire to be honored\nspurs them on to exceptional achi\nevements.\nOne-Minute Test Answers\n1. Nelson T. Johnson.\n2 Winter officially begins at\n1:22 pm.. Eastern Standard Time,\nDec. 22, this year.\n3. Warren G. Harding, Repub\nlican, and James M. Cox, Demo\ncrat.\nWEDNESDAY. NOVEMBER 24, 1937.\ntO. O. Mclntyre\nI don't recall owning a single book\nof verse. Yet in the past ten years\nI have read dozens of the poets,\nold and new. and the majority of\nmy book purchases have been those\nof poems.\nAmong the most widely traveled\nmarried couples in America are the\nWatterson Rothackers. who divide\ntheir time when in this country\nlargely between New York and\nHollywood. Rothacker, as originator\nof a filming process in the early\ndays of motion pictures, retired,\nsensible fellow, before recahing 40.\nHis first gesture was to see the\nworld, which he has with his wife\ncircled many times. Since that\nfirst swing they have traveled to\nout-of-way nooks left largely to\nthose who exploit sight-seeing in\nthe travalogues.\nThe young George Vanderbilts\nwith a $300,000 yearly income, have\nalso become thorough-going travel\ners among the Amerircan young\nsters, He had made several journ\neys into the jungles of Africa and\nBorneo with scientific expeditions\nbefore his recent marriage. For a\nhoneymoon trip, he took his bride\naround the world, and since then\ntheir time is spent studying maps\nfor new places to see on the world\u2019s\nouter rim.\nI mosey over to Grand Central\nnow and then just to watch a crack\ntrain pull out. Several gate-men\nknow I\u2019m a \u201ctrain nut\u201d and wave\nme through. There\u2019s no transporta\ntion thrill to me like the conductor\u2019s\ncry of \u201cBoard!\" the convulsive jerk\nand strain of a train getting in to\nLEGAL ADVERTISEMENT\nSUMMONS\nNo. 17733\nIN THE SUPERIOR COURT OF\nTHE STATE OF CALIFORNIA\nIN AND FOR THE COUNTY OF\nIMPERIAL.\nIMPERIAL IRRIGATION\nDISTRICT. Plaintiff\nvs.\nE. M. PEASE, et al.,\nDefendants.\nHarry W. Horton and Geo. R\nKirk, Attorneys for Plaintiff.\nTHE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF\nCALIFORNIA SEND GREETINGS\nTO:\nE. M. PEASE. THE FIRST NA\nTIONAL BANK OF POMONA, a\nCorporation, a National Banking\nAssociation, ELMER L. HENDER\nSON, CLARK HORSFORD, JEAN\nSMITH FJERESTAD. CHAS. R.\nSTEAD, HUBERT LEBUS. H. C\nCLARK, JOHN DOE, JANE DOE\nRICHARD ROE, JOHN DOE COM\nPANY. a Corporation, and RICH\nARD ROE COMPANY, a Co-part\nnership, Defendants.\nYou Are Hereby Directed to Ap\npear and answer the Complaint in\nan action entitled as above, brought\nagainst you in the Superior Court\nof the County of Imperial, State of\nCalifornia, within ten days after\nthe service on you of this Summons\n\u2014if served within this county: or\nwithin thirty days if served else\nwhere.\nAnd you are hereby notified that\nunless you appear and answer as\nabove required, the said plaintiff\nwill take judgment for any money\nor damages demanded in the com\nplaint, as arising upon contract, or\nit will apply to the Court for any\nother relief demanded in the Com\nplaint.\nGiven under my hand and the\nseal of the Superior Court of the\nCounty of Imperial. State of Cali\nfornia, this 30th day of June. 1937.\nw j McClelland.\n(SEAL) County Clerk\nBy G. O KENYON,\nBy 0. 0. Mclntyre\nmotion for its glide off into the\nfathoms of darkness, the tail light\ngleaming red. Airplanes travel is\nexciting, but only in the takeoff\nand landing. A liner voyage Is the\nsame calibre \u2014after a few hours only\nthe monotony of vast expanse of\nwater. There\u2019s no time on a train\nwhen a traveler cannot look out\nthe window and feel the thrill of\nadventure.\nA DETROIT sanatorium promis\ning a drink cure in three days,\noverlooked a promotional angle by\nnot throwing in the day after free.\nLEGAL ADVERTISEMENT\nCERTIFICATE OF DOING BUSI\nNESS UNDER FICTITIOUS\nNAME\nNOTICE is hereby given that the\nundersigned Gene Higgins is tran\nsacting business in the City of El\nCentro. County of Imperial, State\nof California under the name of\nGolden Valley Dairy.\nThat his full name and place of\nresidence is as follows:\nGene Higgins, two miles West of\nthe City Limits of El Centro on the\nSan Diego Highway; Route 2, Box\n198, El Centro, California.\nGENE HIGGINS.\nSTATE OF CALIFORNIA\nCOUNTY OF IMPERIAL ss.\nOn this 9th day of November, 1937,\nbefore me, L. Lee Nuffer, a Notary\nPublic in and for the County of\nImperial, State of California, per\nsonally appeared Gene Higgins,\nknown to me to be the person whose\nname is subscribed to the within\ninstrument and acknowledged to me\nthat he executed the same.\nIN WITNESS WHEREOF, I have\nhereunto set my hand and affixed\nmy official seal the day and year\nin this certificate first above\nwritten.\nL. I,EE NUFFER,\nNotary Public in and for said\nState and County.\n(Notarial Seal)\nN 10 17 24. D 1\nNOTICE OF SALE OF PROPERTY\nTO SATISFY LIEN Of' KEEPER\nOF HOTEL, INN. OR FUR\nNISHED APARTMENT\nHOUSE FOR GUESTS\nCHARGES\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN\nthat Allied Properties, a hotel, inn\nand furnished apartment house\nkeeper, will on the 10th day of\nDecember, 1937. at the hour of 10\no\u2019clock A M., at the American Stor\nage Building, 3636 Beverly Boule\nvard. in the City of Los Angeles.\nCounty of Los Angeles, State of\nCalifornia, sell at public auction to\nthe highest bidder, the following\nlots of baggage and other property,\nto satisfy charges due from tenants\nor guests and for costs.\nThe names of the debtors, the\namount due from each and a brief\ndescription of the property to be\nsold is as follows:\nLot No. I\u2014Mrs. Henry Busse,\n$27.60. one bag, contents unknown;\nLot No. 2\u2014J. A. Hennessey, $36.19,\none Gladstone bag, contents un\nknown;\nLot No. 3\u2014Captain C. A. Mc\u00dfride,\n$44.40, one suit case, contents un\nknown;\nLot No. 4\u2014Ruth Steward. $38.35,\none suitcase, contents unknown.\nDATED: Nov. 9, 1937\nCOL. E. C. JENKINS.\nLicensed Auctioneer.\nALLIED PROPERTIES\nBy B. H. DORR,\nOffice Manager.\nN 10 17 24. D 1.\nPOST-PRESS WANT ADS\nAre Husiness PullerB\nFamous Sayings\nGod governs the world, and we have only to do our\nduty wisely, and leave the issue to Him. \u2014oJhn Jay.\nThe present session of Congress\nis beginning to resemble the meet\ning of that western frontier debat\ning society, whose president an\nnounced that the evening\u2019s topic\nwould be \"What\u2019s this country\ncoming to?\u201d with the high school\nteacher taking the affirmative and\nhimself the negative.\nWhich is to say that while Con\ngress is full of talk about what this\ncountry may be coming to, it is\nhaving a mortally hard time decid\ning just what the affirmative and\nnegative sides of the issue should\nbe.\nThere is the matter of the bud\nget, for instance. Congress wants\nto see government expenditures cut,\nbut the cutting tool has a handle\nlike a red-hot poker. The army and\nthe navy are costing enormous\nsums, and bids fair to cast more;\nbut with the world in the state it\nis in, the army and the navy look\nlike first-rate insurance which is\nworth whatever it may cost.\nThen there is relief\u2014a stupend\nously expensive thing, which must\nbe bitten into pretty materially if\nwe are to get our government costs\nAuction Philosophy\nFolks. I don't oiame Penny Rich\nmond for bragging on the big cat\nfish he caught and he had me\ncome down to his home and look at\nthe fish swimming in the tub;\nbut wny Milton Ginn mot Zinn)\nshould give a Democratic post\nmaster this fish is some thing else\nand should be investigated by Mr.\nFarley sounds fishy to me. By the\nway, John Wagoner caught an\neight pound catfish last week and\nhe caught this fish on liver bait,\nnot Democratic Bait.\nIt begins to look like this spe\nvial session of congress has the\njitters and the most of \u2019em are\nsore because they had to go back\nto work so soon.\nI look for the biggest crowd we\never had at a football game to be\non hand Thanksgiving day. Boys,\nwait until after the game to eat\nthat turkey and you boys from\nCalexico, if you don\u2019 eat before\nyou come it's going to make you\nawful late for dinner.\nThe Zinnerie clan, 35 strong\nwill gather at our place for\nThanksgiving dinner. We are old\nfashioned and believe wherever\npossible the children and grand\nchildren should gather around\ngrandpa and grandma\u2019s table on\nThanksgiving day. and I am migh\nty thankful to have my mother\nwith us on that day for she is\nmother, grandmother, and great\ngrand mother of the Zinnerie\ntribe.\nI'll be seein\u2019 you,\nYOU haven\u2019t read ALL the NEWS\nuntil you READ the ADS\nNOTICE INVITING BIDS\nNotice is hereby given that seal\ned bids will be received by the\nBoard of Supervisors of the Coun\nty of Imperial, State of California,\nat the office of W. J. McClelland,\nClerk of said Board of Supervisors,\nin the Court House in the City of\nEl Centro, County and State afore\nsaid, up to and including the 6th\nday of December. 1937, at two\no\u2019clock P.M. for the furnishing of\nall necessary labor, materials and\nequipment for the erection and\nconstruction of an annex to the\nCounty Hospital situated on the\nCounty Farm of said county and\nbelonging to said county, the same\nto be done in accordance with the\nplans and specifications therefor\nas amended Novetpber 18. 1937, on\nfile in the office of said Clerk.\nEach bidder is required to accom\npany his bid with a certified check\nor a cashier\u2019s check payable to the\nCounty of Imperial for an amount\nequal to 10 per cent of the amount\nof his bid, all checks to be return\ned to the unsuccessful bidders at\nthe time of acceptance of bid by\nsaid Board of Supervisors and to\nthe successful bidder upon his sign\ning a contract and executing and\nfiling with said W. J. McClelland,\nClerk of said Board of Supervisors,\nat his said office, a bond with good\nand suficient sureties, the same to\nbe approved by said Board of Super\nvisors: the same to be conditioned\nfor the faithful performance of\nthe terms of the contract, and also\na bond or the payment for all\nlabor to be performed in the execu\ntion of this contract and for all\nmaterials furnished in accordance\ntherewith as provided by Chapter\n303 Statutes of 1919 as amended.\nAll bids must be addressed to the\nBoard of Supervisors. El Centro,\nCalifornia, in care of W. J. Mc-\nClelland, Clerk of the Board of\nSupervisors; and such bid must be\nenclosed in a sealed envelope and\nendorsed \u201cbid for furnishing labor,\nmaterial and equipment for erec\ntion of annex to county hospital\".\nSaid board of Supervisors reserves\nthe right to reject any and all\nbids.\nBidders\u2019 attention is called to the\nprovisions of Sections 1770 to 1781\nboth inclusive of Labor Code of\nthe State of California, which re\nquire Boards of Supervisors in ad\nvertising for bids for work and\nmaterial to ascertain and deter\nmine the prevailing rate of per\ndiem wages for each craft or type\nof workman or mechanic needed\nto execute the contract which is to\nbe awarded; notice is hereby given\nto bidders that under the provisions\nof said Sections said Board of\nSupervisors has ascertained and\ndetermined such prevailing rate of\nper diem wages to be as follows:\nPer Hour\nBricklayer $l.OO\nBricklayer Apprentice 80\nCarpenters 1.12 'A\nCompressor Operator 100\nConcrete Finishers 1.00\nConcrete Mixerman .90\nElectrician 1.25\nBruce Catton Says:\nVirile Industry Can Solve Our Problems\nBy D. L. ZINN\nLEGAL ADVERTISEMENT\ndown to anything resembling nor\nmal. But while Congress sidles up to\nthis subject, the Cassadra voices of\nthe conference of mayors ring in\nits ears, warning that to cut re\nlief will be to invite trouble by\nthe carload lot.\nMayor LaGuradia of New York\nsays bluntly that relief is going\nto cost more, not less. The present\nbusiness recession, he warns, means\nincreased unemployment; far from\ntapering off, the relief load is due\nto increase, and increase material\nly, in the coming winter.\nMayor LaGuardia is followed by\nMayor Harold H. Burton of Clev\nland, a conservative Republican.\nConsehvative Burton talks just\nlike Left-Wing LaGuardia, when\nrelief is mentioned.\nCut off the federal relief pro\ngram, says Mayor Burton, and in\nCleveland \u201c100.000 people will be\ncompelled to choose between star\nvation and a lawless search for\nfood.\u201d\nOther mayors talk in the same\nvein; and from their remarks one\nsenses that the relief load, onerous\nthough it is, is something that can\nneither be talked away nor ignor\ned. We still have this enormfati\nundigested mass of unemploy4|\nmen; humanitarian reasons aside,\nwe cannot, in sheer self-defense,\ndo anything but continue to carry\nit as long as it exists.\nWhich seems to indicate, then,\nthat our immediate salvation may\nnot lie in the direction of cutting\nexpenses and slicing into the de\nficit. We should stop spending\nscores of millioins on relief, but\nwe can't do it while need exists;\nthe need will go on existing until\nprivate industry is able to absorb\nthe jobless workers.\nSo Congress might well think\nabout industry instead of the fed\neral treasury, for a while. It might\nthink about that delicate, tenuous\nthing called confidence, and how\nit can be restored; about the pro\nposition that if government can\u2019t\nget business back on its feet, it\ncould try letting business get back\nunaided\u2014and unhampered. For\nour problem can be solved, ap\nparently, only in terms of a genu\nine business revival.\nYom wffl *n|oy th* r*\u00abtfuln*M, \u00abom\nfort and friendly ipirit of Th* Embaiay.\nEatlly occ*itlbl* to th* downtown bu\u00bb-\nln*ti Metlon and point* int*r**t...\ny\u00abt h**t outtid* th* cong*it*d distriA\nRATIti\n\u2022\u2022obi* with both\n\u2022Inpl* with both |XO*\nOWNK AN\u00bb OtHATI* (T\nIO\u00bb ANGELES INVESTMENT\nLEGAL ADVERTISEMENT\nElectrician Helper 65\nForeman Trades 1.25\nForeman Labor 80\nHod Carriers 1.00\nLabor (common) 55\nLabor (plasterers) 83 1-3\nLabor (mortar mixer) 83 1-3\nLabor (skilled) 62 Va\nLathers 1.25\nPainters and Paperhangers, 1.10\nPlasterers 1.25\nPlumbers and pipe fitters 1.25\nRoofer (shingle) $1.25\nRoofer (helper) 75\nSheet metal worker\u2014in-\ncluding corrugated iron,\nTile Setter 1.25\nTruck Driver\n(15,500 and under) 75\nTruck Driver\n(15.500 and over) 80\nSKILLED LABORERS\nConcrete Spreaders 68\nHelpers\u2014building trades .60\nAlso that general prevailing rate\nfor legal holidays and overtime is\none and one-half times the above\nrate; also that the provisions of the\nabove mentioned code require that\nthe bidder who is awarded the\ncontract shall pay not less than the\nprevailing rate of per diem wages\nas ascertained and determined by\nsaid Board of Supervisors as above\nset forth to all laborers, workmen\nand mechanics in the execution of\nthe proposed contract. Attention\nof bidders is also called to the\nvisions of Sections 1850 to 1854, b<fl|\ninclusive, of the Labor Code of\nState of California, which prohibit\nany contractor or sub-contractor\nupon any public works from em\nploying thereon any alien, except\ning in cases of extraordinary emer\ngency. etc., and provides a penalty\nfor violation of the terms of the\nsections of the Labor Code of Cali\nornia above mentioned.\nAttention of bidders is also called\nto the provisions of Sections 1810\nto 1816, both inclusive, of said Labor\nCode which provide that the time\nof service of any workman em\nployed on public work in the State\nof California whether the work is\ndone by contract or otherwise, is\nlimited and restricted to eight hours\nduring any one calendar day and\nmake it unlawful to permit any\nworkman to labor more than eight\nhours during any one calendar day\nexcept in cases of extraordinary\nemergencies, and said sections pro\nvide for a penalty for violation\nthereof. Any prospective bidder who\ndesires to take a set of the plans\nand specifications from the office\nof the said W. J. McClelland, Clerk\nof said Board of Supervisors, shall\nreturn the same to said Clerk with\nin five days thereafter and shall\ndeposit witii said Clerk at the time\nof taking said plans and specifica\ntions the sum of $5.00 to guarantee\ntheir prompt return.\nBy Order of the Board of Super\nvisors.\nDATED this 18th day of Nove\u00ae\nher, 1937.\nw. j. McClelland.\nClerk of the Board of Supervisors\nof the County of Imperial.\nN. 19-30 incl.","height":"29404","width":"23264"}}
